When the Fe3+ was added into B-CDs solution, there was obvious fluorescence quenching phenomenon (Fig. 8
                           ). To explore the specificity and selectivity of B-CDs to Fe3+ detection in complex environments, we investigated the fluorescence intensity response to various interfering substances, including metal ions (K+, Na+, Mg2+, Ca2+, Ag+, Fe3+, Ni2+, Zn2+, Hg2+, Zr4+, Cd2+, Sr2+, Sn2+, Co2+, Mn2+, Cr(IV)), amino acids (Tryptophan, Threonine, Lysine, Glycine, Phenylalanine, Tyrosine, Arginine, Cysteine, Aspartic acid, Serine), antibiotics (Florfenicol, Erythromycin, Streptomycin, Tetracycline, Chloramphenicol, Chlortetracycline, Kanamycin) and different substances such as Glucose, EDTA, Thiourea, Sulfonamide, Ascorbic acid (Fig. 9
                           A–C). The results shown that B-CDs only had a strong response to Fe3+ and barely no response to other substances, suggesting the high selectivity for Fe3+ detection. When possible interference substances coexisted, the other substances no effect on the fluorescence quenching caused by the Fe3+ ions. This result futher indicated that B-CDs had a high selectivity for Fe3+ (Fig. S1).

Additionally, when the tetracycline antibiotics was added into S-CDs solution, we recorded the change of visual fluorescence and noticed obvious fluorescence quenching phenomena with increased tetracycline antibiotics (Fig. 11
                           ). This suggested that we could observe the visual change with our S-CDs in detection of tetracycline antibiotics. Subsequently, we examined our S-CDs fluorescence response to other interfering substances and figured that our S-CDs was highly sensitive to tetracycline antibiotics with an obvious response and fluorescence quenching (Fig. 12
                           ). When other interference substances were mixed with TCs, the effect of coexistent substances can be neglected, suggesting the specificity of S-CDs to TCs detection (Fig. S2). Overall, these results proved the specificity and sensitivity of our S-CDs for detecting tetracycline antibiotics.

To evaluate the reliability and practical application of our B-CDs and S-CDs, we decided to examine Fe3+ and TCs content in bottled mineral water and facial mask. As described previously, we obtained the actual samples from a local supermarket. The actual samples were tested and Fe3+ and TCs was not detected. Next, we added different concentrations of Fe3+ (15, 30, 45 μmol L−1) to bottled mineral water and assessed the performance of our B-CDs. As excepted, the recovery rate was 92.78%∼103.33% (RSD<0.39%). As well, we mixed three different concentrations of TCs (5, 10, 15 μmol L−1) with facial mask sample and evaluated the performance of our S-CDs, the recovery rate was 84.46%∼115.40% (RSD<2.94%). Overall, these results proven that our B-CDs and S-CDs had high practicability and accuracy in actual sample detection (Table 1
                         and Table 2
                        ).
